<item>
  <title>What PCA actually does: yield curve worked examples</title>
  <dc:creator>Kelvin Wong</dc:creator>
  <link>https://kelvin1189.github.io/actuarial-modeling-notes/posts/pca-yc/</link>
  <description><![CDATA[ 





<p>This series is a worked exposition of Principal Component Analysis applied to yield curve data. It began as personal notes from two encounters with PCA — once at work, looking at a Dynamic Nelson-Siegel model and noticing the connection to PCA’s empirical factors, and again while preparing for the SOA SRM exam. The mechanism only really clicked for me when I drew a 2-tenor rotation plot and could finally <em>see</em> what the algorithm was doing to the data.</p>
<p>The series is structured around that visualisation. <a href="00-intro/index.qmd">Article 0</a> introduces the technique from first principles: the stress-testing problem it solves, the mathematics that produces the eigenvalue equation, and the reason maximising variance is the right thing to want. <a href="01-2tenor-toy/index.qmd">Article 1</a> makes the rotation mechanism visualisable on two tenors. <a href="02-3tenor/index.qmd">Article 2</a> extends to three tenors and demonstrates the canonical Level / Slope / Curvature decomposition. PCA on real Taiwan TWD data is the subject of <a href="../ics-dns-twd-yc/03-pca-twd/index.qmd">Article 3 of the DNS series</a> (forthcoming) rather than this one.</p>
